{{Infobox university | name = Institute for Aerospace Studies | native_name = | image_name = | image_size = | image_alt = | caption = | motto = | motto_lang = | motto_eng = | former_names = | established = {{Start date|1949}} | closed = | type = | parent = [[University of Toronto Faculty of Applied Science and Engineering|Faculty of Applied Science and Engineering]] | affiliation = [[University of Toronto]] | city = [[Downsview]] | province = [[Ontario]] | country = [[Canada]] | coor = | dean = | rector = | director = | head_label = | head = | academic_staff = | administrative_staff = | students = | undergrad = | postgrad = | doctoral = | alumni = | colours = | symbol = | website = | logo = }}
The '''University of Toronto Institute for Aerospace Studies''' ('''UTIAS''', {{IPAc-en|j|uː|ˈ|t|aɪ|ə|s}} {{respell|yoo|TY|əs}}) is an advanced research facility for [[aeronautics]] and [[aerospace engineering]], located in the [[Downsview]] district of [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. Established in 1949 by founding Director Gordon N. Patterson, the institute is managed by the [[University of Toronto Faculty of Applied Science and Engineering]] and mainly receives funding from governmental agencies such as the [[National Research Council (Canada)|National Research Council]], the [[Department of National Defence (Canada)|Department of National Defence]] and the [[Canadian space agency|Canadian Space Agency]]. Notable international sponsors include the [[European Space Agency]], [[Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory]], [[Max-Planck-Institut für Plasmaphysik]], [[NASA Ames Research Center]] and the [[United Kingdom Atomic Energy Authority]].
==History==
In 1970, the institute was involved in the emergency rescue of the [[Apollo 13]] astronauts, after the mission was aborted by a major accident en route to the Moon. UTIAS was contacted for assistance due to its expertise in shockwaves and aerospace dynamics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.utias.utoronto.ca/AssetFactory.aspx?did=220 |title=An Account of UTIAS Involvement in the Rescue of Apollo 13 |last=Sullivan |first=Phil |publisher=University of Toronto Institute for Aerospace Studies}}</ref> Engineers and scientists at UTIAS calculated the amount of pressure needed to separate the [[Lunar Module]] from the [[Apollo Command/Service Module|Command/Service Module]] without damaging the hatch, allowing the crew to survive the re-entry to Earth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.casmuseum.org/common/PDF/pressreleases/CASM_Apollo_13_Release_2010.pdf |title=Canadians celebrate Canada's contribution to the safe return of the Apollo 13 astronauts on 40th anniversary of original space mission |publisher=[[Canadian Air and Space Museum]]}}</ref> Observing the 40th anniversary of the incident in 2010, lunar module pilot [[Fred Haise]] wrote a letter thanking the UTIAS team for its contribution.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aiac.ca/success-stories/utias-bringing-apollo-13-home.aspx |title=UTIAS - Bringing Apollo 13 Home |publisher=Aerospace Industries Association of Canada |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523072844/http://www.aiac.ca/success-stories/utias-bringing-apollo-13-home.aspx |archivedate=2010-05-23 |df= }}</ref>
In recent years,{{when|date=October 2013}} the institute has produced the world's first [[microwave]]-powered aircraft, the world's first engine-powered [[ornithopter]] (both inventions of [[James DeLaurier]]), and Canada's first [[space telescope]], [[Microvariability and Oscillations of STars telescope|MOST]]. The major expertise areas represented are [[aerospace engineering|aircraft design]], particularly at [[subsonic flight|subsonic]] speeds, [[flight simulation]], space [[mechatronics]] and [[robotics]], [[Microsatellite (spaceflight)|microsatellite]] technology, [[computational fluid dynamics]] and [[nuclear fusion]]. The institute's partners in the aerospace industry include [[Bombardier Aerospace]], [[MD Robotics]] (formerly [[Spar Aerospace]]) and [[General Atomics]]. It operates the [[Canadian Advanced Nanospace eXperiment Program]] for the study and testing of nanosatellite technology.{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}
